        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Restaurant Fire Safety Requirements in St. Paul, MN: What Every Operator Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">St. Paul's Grand Avenue restaurant corridor, the Lowertown arts and dining district, and the Capitol area food scene have made the capital city one of Minnesota's most active restaurant fire safety compliance markets. Saint Paul Fire Department enforces Minnesota State Fire Code requirements including semi-annual NFPA 96 kitchen suppression inspections. Here's what every St. Paul restaurant operator needs to know.</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">NFPA 96 Kitchen Suppression Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">All commercial cooking operations in St. Paul producing grease-laden vapors must install and maintain an automatic wet chemical fire suppression system under NFPA 96. This applies to restaurants, bars with food service, hotel kitchens, and corporate cafeterias. St. Paul's restaurant compliance is anchored by Grand Avenue's mile-long strip of independently owned restaurants and bars — one of the Twin Cities' most concentrated dining corridors — and the growing Lowertown food and arts scene. Minnesota State Fire Code requires semi-annual NFPA 96 inspection for all commercial cooking operations.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Semi-Annual Inspection Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 96 requires kitchen suppression systems to be inspected and serviced semi-annually — twice per year — by a licensed contractor. Records must be maintained on-site and available for Saint Paul Fire Department inspection. Semi-annual means every six months from the last inspection date, not twice per calendar year.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Hood Cleaning Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 96 requires hood cleaning at intervals based on cooking volume: quarterly for high-volume operations (solid fuel cooking, charbroiling, wok cooking, high-volume fryers), semi-annually for moderate volume, annually for low-volume like pizza ovens. Hood cleaning records must be maintained on-site.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Class K Fire Extinguisher</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">A Class K extinguisher must be within 30 feet of all cooking surfaces producing grease-laden vapors. Class K units are specifically designed for cooking oil fires — standard ABC dry chemical is not an adequate substitute. Class K units require annual inspection alongside other extinguishers.</p>
