        <div class="flex flex-col gap-3 mb-8"><div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-red-light rounded-lg border border-red-200"><span class="text-red-brand font-bold flex-shrink-0">!</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-700">Overdue semi-annual suppression in Grand Avenue restaurant district — busy seasonal operations defer second annual inspection</span></div><div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-red-light rounded-lg border border-red-200"><span class="text-red-brand font-bold flex-shrink-0">!</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-700">Missing Class K extinguishers in Lowertown restaurant and bar kitchens</span></div><div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-red-light rounded-lg border border-red-200"><span class="text-red-brand font-bold flex-shrink-0">!</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-700">Hood cleaning frequency insufficient for high-volume Grand Avenue operations</span></div><div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-3 bg-red-light rounded-lg border border-red-200"><span class="text-red-brand font-bold flex-shrink-0">!</span><span class="text-sm text-gray-700">Space heater placement violations near combustibles during winter months</span></div></div>
        <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Do St. Paul restaurants need to do anything special for winter fire safety compliance?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Minnesota's cold winters create fire safety concerns beyond standard compliance. Space heaters in restaurant entry areas or server stations are a leading cause of restaurant fires in cold climates — ensure they are commercial-rated and not placed near combustible materials. Kitchen suppression semi-annual inspections should not be deferred during winter months — schedule both your spring and fall inspections proactively.</p></div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 mb-8"><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Does every St. Paul restaurant need a kitchen fire suppression system?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Yes. All commercial cooking operations in St. Paul producing grease-laden vapors must have an automatic wet chemical suppression system under NFPA 96 and the Minnesota State Fire Code / IFC. This applies to restaurants, bars with food service, hotel kitchens, and corporate cafeterias.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How often does kitchen fire suppression need to be inspected in St. Paul?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">NFPA 96 requires semi-annual inspection — twice per year — for all commercial kitchen suppression systems. Inspection must be performed by a licensed contractor and documented. The Saint Paul Fire Department enforces this requirement.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How much does kitchen suppression inspection cost in St. Paul?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">$165–$360 per system per system. Budget for two inspections annually.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What is the most common kitchen fire safety violation in St. Paul?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Common violations in St. Paul include: Overdue semi-annual suppression in Grand Avenue restaurant district — busy seasonal operations defer second annual inspection; Missing Class K extinguishers in Lowertown restaurant and bar kitchens.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Who licenses kitchen suppression contractors in MN?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">The Minnesota State Fire Marshal Division ((651) 201-7200) licenses fire protection contractors statewide. Verify your suppression contractor holds current MN credentials before scheduling service.</p></div></div>
